<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871020-0031 </DOCNO><HL> New York Times Co.Profit Climbed 22%In the Third Period</HL><DD> 10/20/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> NYTAEARNINGS (ERN)PUBLISHING (PUB) </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   New York Times Co. said third-quarter net income jumped 22%, bolstered by a 13% gain in operating profit at its newspaper group.    The company, which also has magazine and broadcasting interests, said net rose to $32.6 million, or 40 cents a share, from $26.7 million, or 33 cents a share, in the year-earlier period. Revenue climbed 9.8% to $406.5 million from $370.1 million.    Advertising linage at the company's flagship New York Times grew 5.1% in the quarter to 28.3 million lines. For the nine months, linage also rose 5.1% to 89.3 million lines. Weekday circulation increased 2.1% for the six months ended Sept. 30, to 1,022,900; Sunday circulation rose 0.3% to 1,589,300 during the six-month period.    For the nine months, net rose 21% to $117.8 million, or $1.44 a share, from $97.5 million, or $1.20 a share, in the 1986 nine months. Sales grew 8.3% to $1.24 billion from $1.15 billion.    Results in the year-earlier periods include a pretax charge of $8.5 million, or five cents a share, relating to litigation.    The company said its group of 32 regional newspapers posted a 5.6% increase in advertising volume for the third quarter and a 3% rise for the nine months. Those figures exclude the results for the Gwinnett Daily News and two other publications acquired in July.    The company said operating profit at its magazine group slipped to $6.2 million in the quarter from $6.7 million. The group's nine-month operating profit was flat at $21.5 million, the company said. </TEXT></DOC>